Smitham is defined as the small lumps of ore which free miners scavenged because they were exempt from payment of lot and cope duties. This practice was brought to an end in 1760 when the Duke of Devonshire challenged the practice in chancery on the basis that mine owners were breaking larger lumps down to avoid taxation.

Source: The Politics of Social Conflict: The Peak Country, 1520-1770 by Andy Wood published by Cambridge University Press